<Author>odyssea
<Content>This could be the answer for your trip to Berlin Have just spent four days in one of the small single rooms on the top floor with en suite facilities which are offered to budget travellers or `visiting artists'. On the plus side, the rooms were immaculately clean with an exceptionally comfortable bed. Mine was a `themed' room too which surprised me as I thought that these artistic flourishes only extended to the pricier accommodation. The reception staff were pleasant and helpful with the exception of one member of staff who struggled with English and did not know the price of breakfast. (Sounds petty? Thank goodness I wasn't a hotel inspector) The hotel itself enjoys a first-rate location just minutes away from Unter den Linden, the Reichstag and the Brandenburg Gate. And it's beautiful to look at. On the minus side... There is no way round this. The hotel is next to a high speed railway line. Some of the rooms are just metres away. Mine wasn't - but the noise was thunderous at times - as if the train was heading straight for the room! Anyone who has stayed here will know I am not exaggerating! This is scarcely the hotel's fault but I would advise anyone who's sensitive to noise to steer well clear.The budget quarter where I stayed is VERY spartan - those who value home comforts can forget it. It's hostel standard and if that's what you want, great. Otherwise, look elsewhere!There are no facilities like a bar in the hotel itself -just a drinks machine. In fairness there is a restaurant next door - Weinguy- which seems to have struck a deal with the hotel and serves breakfast to guests. It's NOT included in the price of the room and will cost you eight euros. Having said that it was worth the money and the surroundings were lovely. I got some very good feedback about their business lunch and evening meals.Because I wasn't staying in the customised rooms designed by artists, I don't know if I am that great a spokesperson for this hotel. I would however be interested to hear what you tripadvisor members have to say about this pricier part of the tariff 
